comment.shortText:
A channel is the basic building block of Realtime
and narrows the scope of data flow to subscribed clients.
You can think of a channel as a chatroom where participants are able to see who's online
and send and receive messages.

self option enables client to receive message it broadcast
ack option instructs server to acknowledge that broadcast message was received
key option is used to track presence payload across clients
Initializes the Socket.
The string WebSocket endpoint, ie, "ws://example.com/socket", "wss://example.com", "/socket" (inherited host & protocol)

self option enables client to receive message it broadcast
ack option instructs server to acknowledge that broadcast message was received
key option is used to track presence payload across clients
Connects the socket, unless already connected.
Returns the current state of the socket.
Disconnects the socket.
A numeric status code to send on disconnect.
A custom reason for the disconnect.
Returns all created channels
Returns `true` is the connection is open.
Logs the message.
comment.text: For customized logging, `this.logger` can be overridden.

comment.shortText: Push out a message if the socket is connected.
comment.text: If the socket is not connected, the message gets enqueued within a local buffer, and sent out when a connection is next established.

A RealtimeChannel instance

A channel is the basic building block of Realtime
and narrows the scope of data flow to subscribed clients.
You can think of a channel as a chatroom where participants are able to see who's online
and send and receive messages.
Sets the JWT access token used for channel subscription authorization and Realtime RLS.
A JWT string.
Creates an event handler that listens to changes
Realtime feature (broadcast, presence, or postgres_changes)
Pre-defined and custom values specific to the Realtime feature

Event to listen to. If listening to postgres_changes type
then this value is one of INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, *
Function to be invoked when event handler is triggered
Subscribe registers your client with the server
Leaves the channel.
comment.text:
Unsubscribes from server events, and instructs channel to terminate on server.
Triggers onClose() hooks.

To receive leave acknowledgements, use the a `receive` hook to bind to the server ack, ie:
channel.unsubscribe().receive("ok", () => alert("left!") )
